Mean danceability against mode name

song_data<- fromJSON("json data.json")

mean_data <- song_data %>%
  group_by(mode_name)%>%
  summarise(mean_danceability = mean(danceability, na.rm= TRUE))%>%
  arrange(mean_danceability)
mean_data
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   mode_name mean_danceability
##   <chr>                 <dbl>
## 1 major                 0.476
## 2 minor                 0.479
ggplot()+
  geom_jitter(data= song_data,
              aes(x =danceability, y= mode_name),
              height=0.4,
              color= "#CD84FD") +
  geom_point(data=mean_data,
             aes(x=mean_danceability, y=mode_name),
color="#FDAB84",
alpha= 0.4,
size=6,
shape=19) +
  labs( title= "Danceability of major and minor songs",
        x="Danceability",
        y="Mode Name")+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill ="#FBF8BE"))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

Mean danceability against duration in minutes

song_data<- fromJSON("json data.json")%>%
  mutate(duration_min= duration_ms/1000/60)


danceability_mean <- song_data$danceability %>% mean(na.rm = TRUE) %>% round(1)


ggplot()+
  geom_jitter(data=song_data,
              aes(x=danceability, 
                  y= duration_min),
                  color="#3945F5",
                  alpha=0.7) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = danceability_mean,
             alpha= 0.5,
             color ="#C1BEFB")+
  labs( title= "Danceability compared to the duration in minutes",
        x="Danceability",
        y="Duration in Minutes")+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill ="#BEF5FB"))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+
  transition_states(danceability)+
  shadow_mark()

Mean danceability against year released, subsetted by mode name

song_data<- fromJSON("json data.json")

release_data <- song_data %>%
  mutate(year_released = release_date %>% str_sub(1, 4) %>% parse_number()) %>%
  count(year_released, danceability, mode_name)



release_data%>%
ggplot()+
  geom_line(aes(x=year_released,
                y=danceability),
                color= "#FF0B4D")+
  facet_wrap(vars(mode_name))+
  labs( title= "Danceability compared to the year released subsetted by the mode of the song",
        x="Year released",
        y="Danceability")+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill ="#FDC9F6"))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+
  
  geom_hline(data=mean_data,
             aes(yintercept =mean_danceability),
                  alpha=0.3)

About my story and visulisations

The story I have decided to tell with my data is how the mean danceability of songs from the ‘Jazz trombone classics’ playlist is affected against different variables. I first compared the mean danceability against the two mode types major and minor in which the mean danceability for minor sings was slightly higher being 0.478 against major which was 0.476. I then compared the mean danceability with the duration of the song in minutes in which I found a general upwards trend between duration and danceability with the mean danceability being approximately 0.49. I then compared danceability and year released, subsetting by mode name and found very similar mean danceability’s for both types of modes regardless of the year released at around 0.44. From my story I can then hence conclude the type of mode having very little impact on the danceability whereas duration and year released seem to have more of an effect.

I chose to make the variable danceability the main focus for my visualisations as jazz is typically a genre people enjoy dancing to and was interested in what other factors have an impact on this rating. I chose year released, duration and mode name to see if there were any particular correlations or connections that I could draw from between that variable and the danceability of the song.

I chose to use geom jitters for my first two visualisations as for my first plot compared danceability with mode name, I am able to easily sub set the two groups while having a very clear idea of the spread of the data through the points and the use of geom point to give a clear indication of the mean for both groups. I used geom jitter in my second visualisation comparing danceability and duration as I was easily able to animate the plot, emphasising the trend of the data and a vertical line to communicate the mean. I used geom line in my final visualisation as the graph type was similar to a time series graph with the line being the most appropriate to communicate this information with a horizontal line to get an overall mean for both subsets.

I applied the grammar of graphics by changing the theme of my visualisations by changing the background colours and removing the grids to make a cohesive aesthetic. I also included a facet in my third visualisation to subset on a third variable and be able to communicate extra information. I also changed the transparency on my mean indicators to still have the emphasis on the data. I added labels to my axis to make what the variables were easy to understand.

Something I tried but didn’t work was trying to group the different levels of danceability into 0.4>, 0.6>, 0.6< to do an animation by group. However, I was not able to find a method of this that produced the desired results so went with a gradual reveal animation.

My overall conclusion would be that visualisation and the grammar of graphics plays a big part about how data is understood and communicated to a general audience and data that is aesthetically pleasing gathers more interest to learn what the data is about.
